NMDS Example

In this example will use the ‘varespec’ and ‘varechem’ data sets in the vegan package to run an NMDS and cluster analysis to examine lichen species communities. We will also be using the source file ‘biostats.R’ developed by Kevin McGarigal at the University of Massachusetts. This source file has a lot of good functions for analyzing ecological data.
(Note that the three lines above this one did not break to a new line in the document.
You need to add 2 spaces at the end of a line if you want the next line to be a new line in the document.)

> # ----- Nonmetric Multidimensionsl Scaling (NMDS) ----- Run an NMDS using
> # Bray-Curtis dissimilarity with 2 dimensions on the species data.
> sp.nmds = metaMDS(varespec, distance = "bray", k = 2, autotransform = FALSE, 
+     trymax = 100, zerodist = "add")
## Run 0 stress 0.1000211 
## Run 1 stress 0.1000211 
## ... procrustes: rmse 1.982038e-05  max resid 5.457578e-05 
## *** Solution reached
> sp.nmds
## 
## Call:
## metaMDS(comm = varespec, distance = "bray", k = 2, trymax = 100,      autotransform = FALSE, zerodist = "add") 
## 
## global Multidimensional Scaling using monoMDS
## 
## Data:     varespec 
## Distance: bray 
## 
## Dimensions: 2 
## Stress:     0.1000211 
## Stress type 1, weak ties
## Two convergent solutions found after 1 tries
## Scaling: centring, PC rotation, halfchange scaling 
## Species: expanded scores based on 'varespec'

Very good NMDS. Two dimensions gave us a stress of 0.1.

Visualize the NMDS

Diagnostic Figures

Here we’ll examine the ordered observations next the NMDS illustrating 1) the goodness of fit for each observation (site) and 2) the location each species plays in the ordination. This is a bit messy, but it’s a good diagnostic figure.

Interpret the Axes

This plot helps you interpret the axes. For example, Axis 1 is composed primarily of Plesch. Axis 2 is composed of Claste, Claarb, etc. Axis 2 is also correlated with AL, Fe, Mn, and Humdepth. Axis 1 is not strongly correlated with soil variables. You can change the axis probability sensitivity by changing the value of ‘p.max’ in the ‘plot()’ lines.
